The National Union of Petroleum and Natural Gas Workers (NUPENG) and the Independent Petroleum Marketers Association of Nigeria (IPMAN) has suspended their two-day strike action in Rivers State. NUPENG and IPMAN members in the state had gone on strike on Wednesday, February 19, 2020, thereby suspending sale of petroleum products at the filling stations. They had accused the Nigerian Army, the Nigerian Security and Civil Defence Corps and Rivers State Taskforce on Street Trading and Illegal Motorparks, of arresting and detaining their trucks and driver’s at will. The development led to rise in the pump price of petroleum products by over 100 percent while transporters also increase their fare by 100 percent. A source close to IPMAN, who pleaded for anonymity, said the suspension of the strike followed a meeting between the Rivers State government and national leadership of NUPENG and IPMAN. The Rivers State Commissioner for Energy and Natural Resources, Peter Medeh, who convened the meeting after the previous one ended in deadlock, had told newsmen earlier in the day that the strike will be suspended at the end of the second meeting.